#compdef email-sleuth
# =============================================================================
# email-sleuth — Kerim Buyukakyuz's "A tool to find and
#          verify email addresses associated with contacts
#          and company websites" — a Rust async CLI that
#          combines (1) per-domain HTML SCRAPING for
#          publicly-listed contact emails, (2) PATTERN
#          GENERATION for common corporate email formats
#          ({first}.{last}@, {f}{last}@, etc.), and (3)
#          multi-modal VERIFICATION via SMTP probing +
#          Office365 API lookups + headless-browser
#          challenges to determine which generated
#          candidates actually exist, all without sending
#          any actual email.
#          Distinguishing from Hunter.io (commercial
#          email-finder SaaS), Snov.io (commercial), Lusha
#          (commercial), Apollo.io (commercial),
#          findemails.com (commercial), and ContactOut
#          (commercial) by:
#            - SELF-HOSTED + OFFLINE-FIRST — no API key,
#              no third-party service, no SaaS dependency;
#              all verification logic runs locally;
#              suitable for compliance-restricted contexts
#              (GDPR data residency, on-prem deployment)
#            - SCRAPER-BASED WEBSITE HARVESTING — uses
#              causal-agent/scraper v0.19 (the dominant
#              Rust HTML parsing + CSS-selector crate;
#              this is the headline CLI library that OPENS
#              Axis 41 on the Rust side; see taxonomy
#              notes below) backed by reqwest + rustls
#              to fetch and parse target-domain pages,
#              extracting any `mailto:` links, contact-
#              page emails in plain text, and email-shaped
#              regex matches from rendered HTML
#            - SMTP VERIFICATION via lettre — uses lettre
#              v0.11 to perform the "Recipient probe"
#              (HELO/EHLO + MAIL FROM + RCPT TO without
#              DATA) which most SMTP servers respond to
#              with a clear ACCEPT/REJECT before any
#              actual email payload is sent.  Hardened
#              with rustls + tokio-rustls + rustls-native-
#              certs for TLS connections
#            - O365 API CHECKS — `--enable-api-checks`
#              activates the Office365 GetCredentialType
#              endpoint probe that returns IfExistsResult
#              (0/1/2/5/6) indicating whether the
#              candidate email is a known Microsoft 365
#              identity.  Faster + more reliable than
#              SMTP for M365-hosted domains
#            - HEADLESS BROWSER CHECKS via fantoccini —
#              `--enable-headless-checks` activates
#              browser-driver-based verification (e.g.
#              Yahoo's "Forgot password?" flow reveals
#              account existence).  Uses fantoccini
#              (WebDriver client) → ChromeDriver +
#              Selenium.  Requires `--chromedriver-path`
#              or `--webdriver-url`
#            - THREE VERIFICATION MODES — `--mode basic`
#              (SMTP only) / `--mode enhanced` (SMTP +
#              API) / `--mode comprehensive` (SMTP + API
#              + headless).  Tradeoff: more methods =
#              slower but higher confidence; basic mode
#              completes in seconds per contact while
#              comprehensive can take 30+ seconds
#            - BATCH MODE via `--input <contacts.json>`
#              — process hundreds/thousands of contacts
#              from a single JSON file with `--concurrency
#              <N>` worker pool; emits results to
#              `--output <results.json>`
#            - SINGLE-CONTACT MODE via `--name "John
#              Doe" --domain example.com` — interactive
#              single-record lookup; emit to file or
#              `--stdout`
#            - DNS RESOLVER TUNING — `--dns-servers
#              "1.1.1.1,8.8.8.8"` + `--dns-timeout
#              <secs>` control which resolvers are used
#              for MX-record lookups (every domain's MX
#              records determine which SMTP server to
#              probe)
#            - CHROMEDRIVER SERVICE MANAGEMENT via
#              `--service start|stop|restart|status|logs`
#              — bundled service manager spawns +
#              monitors a local ChromeDriver process for
#              the headless-checks pipeline; no need to
#              start it manually
#            - TOML CONFIGURATION — `--config-file
#              <path>` loads settings from TOML; CLI
#              flags override file settings
#            - EARLY TERMINATION — `--early-termination-
#              threshold <0..100>` short-circuits the
#              verification loop when confidence exceeds
#              the threshold, avoiding unnecessary slow
#              checks (headless browser probes)
#            - 409+ STARS ON tokenizer-decode/email-
#              sleuth — actively maintained
#          Used by: cold-outreach sales teams seeking
#          self-hosted alternatives to Hunter.io,
#          security researchers performing OSINT email
#          enumeration for permitted penetration testing
#          engagements, recruiters cross-referencing
#          contact lists against domains, and privacy-
#          conscious deployments where transmitting
#          contact data to a SaaS email-finder is
#          prohibited.
#
# SECURITY + AUTHORIZATION NOTE: email-sleuth performs
# active probes against third-party SMTP servers + web
# services.  Use ONLY against domains where you have
# authorization (your own company, explicit pentest
# engagement scope, public records research where the
# target's terms of service permit it).  Rate limits and
# abuse-detection systems may flag aggressive probing.
#
# Author:  Kerim Buyukakyuz <kerim@trylon.ai>
#          (tokenizer-decode on GitHub).
# Source:  https://github.com/buyukakyuz/email-sleuth
#          https://github.com/buyukakyuz/email-sleuth/blob/main/src/main.rs
#          https://github.com/buyukakyuz/email-sleuth/blob/main/Cargo.toml
# Manpage: No traditional manpage; `email-sleuth --help`
#          shows the option list (clap 4.x derive macro
#          generated).  Full docs in repo README.md.
# Library: scraper v0.19 (causal-agent/scraper — the
#          dominant Rust HTML parsing + CSS-selector
#          crate, built on top of servo's html5ever + ego-
#          tree).  This is the headline dependency for
#          this completion's axis-opening role; see
#          taxonomy notes below.  Also clap 4.4 (Axis 1
#          argparse with `derive` + `env` features for
#          env-var-backed flags), reqwest 0.12 (HTTP
#          client with rustls-tls + json + stream
#          features), rustls 0.21 + tokio-rustls 0.24 +
#          rustls-native-certs 0.6 (TLS stack), lettre
#          0.11 (SMTP client with smtp-transport +
#          tokio1-rustls + ring), fantoccini 0.19
#          (WebDriver client for headless-browser
#          checks), trust-dns-resolver 0.23 (custom DNS
#          resolution for MX-record lookups), indicatif
#          0.17 (progress bars), tracing + tracing-
#          subscriber (Axis 9 logging), serde +
#          serde_json + toml (config + I/O), regex 1.10
#          (email-pattern recognition), parking_lot 0.12
#          (sync primitives), openssl-sys 0.9 (vendored
#          for some legacy deps).
